    <!-- Article content -->
    <section class="py-16 px-4">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-lg prose-gray">

        <p class="lead text-xl text-gray-700 font-medium">
          Having a solid strategy has never been more important. But organisations that truly manage to execute it remain the exception. The differentiator is not the quality of the plan — it is the <strong>organisational capacity to turn it into results</strong>.
        </p>

        <h2>40% of value lost: the real cost of the strategy-to-execution gap</h2>
        <p>
          Harvard Business Review estimates that organisations lose an average of <strong>40% of their strategy's potential value</strong> through execution failures. This figure is consistently underestimated by leadership teams — because the loss is gradual, invisible, and rarely attributed to its real cause.
        </p>
        <p>
          The symptoms are well known: delayed projects, missed targets, teams working hard but not in the same direction, decisions constantly escalated to the executive committee. This is not a competence problem. It is a structural execution problem.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-gray-50 border-l-4 border-teal rounded-r-xl p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-2">Why the gap widens</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700">HBR identifies the main cause not in implementation itself, but in how the plan is conceived — too ambitious, too disconnected from the organisation's actual capabilities, and designed without accounting for real execution conditions on the ground.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Organisational health: the predictor executive committees underestimate</h2>
        <p>
          McKinsey's Organisational Health Index (2025–2026) is clear: <strong>healthy organisations are 3x more likely to outperform</strong> their peers over the long term — across all industries.
        </p>
        <p>
          Organisational health, as McKinsey defines it, rests on four core capabilities:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Align</strong> around a shared direction across all levels of the organisation</li>
          <li><strong>Adapt</strong> quickly to external changes without losing coherence</li>
          <li><strong>Execute with rigour</strong> — not occasionally, but repeatably</li>
          <li><strong>Renew</strong> to sustain performance over time</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          A brilliant strategy carried by an unhealthy organisation will produce mediocre results. A sound strategy carried by a healthy organisation will deliver lasting performance. <strong>Organisational health is the prerequisite for any successful strategy execution.</strong>
        </p>

        <h2>The 4 pillars of rigorous execution</h2>
        <p>
          McKinsey (2025) identifies four elements that the best-performing organisations systematically embed in how they operate:
        </p>

        <h3>1. Clear accountability</h3>
        <p>
          Every decision, every deliverable, every objective has an identified owner — and that ownership is real, not diluted across committees. Organisations that execute well know precisely <em>who is accountable for what</em>.
        </p>

        <h3>2. Coordination and control</h3>
        <p>
          Cross-team coordination processes are designed to facilitate execution, not just monitor it. Operating rhythms (short stand-ups, actionable dashboards) allow early detection of deviations and fast correction.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Execution capabilities</h3>
        <p>
          Execution is a craft. High-performing organisations invest in operational skills — project management, performance management, team facilitation — as much as in strategic capabilities.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Motivation to deliver</h3>
        <p>
          Teams execute better when they understand why their contribution matters, when objectives are realistic, and when achievements are recognised. The motivation to deliver is not a "nice to have" — it is a measurable performance driver.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-gray-50 border-l-4 border-teal rounded-r-xl p-6 my-8">
          <p class="font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-1">Diagnostic questions</p>
          <ul class="text-gray-700 space-y-1 text-sm">
            <li>Does everyone in your organisation know exactly what they are accountable for — and can they explain it in 30 seconds?</li>
            <li>Do your management meetings result in concrete decisions, or just "progress updates"?</li>
            <li>Do your managers have the skills to monitor and correct execution — not just to plan?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Link to full version -->
        <div class="not-prose bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-6 my-8">
